🧠 Big Picture First

Both mock and spy are used to test:

Was a method called?

But the timing of expectation is different.

That’s the key difference.

1️⃣ Mock (Expectation Before Execution)

With a mock, you set the expectation before the code runs.

Example
expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email).with(user)

PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)

Here:

You tell RSpec:
👉 “I EXPECT this method to be called.”

Then you run the code.

If method is not called → test fails.

So mock = pre-defined expectation.

2️⃣ Spy (Verify After Execution)

A spy records what happened, and you verify after execution.

Example
allow(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)

expect(NotificationService).to have_received(:send_email).with(user)

Here:

You allow the method (so it can be tracked).

Run the code.

Then check if it was called.

Spy = post-verification.

🔥 Core Difference

| Mock                            | Spy                            |
| ------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| `expect(...).to receive`        | `expect(...).to have_received` |
| Expectation before execution    | Verification after execution   |
| Fails immediately if not called | Fails at verification step     |
| Strict                          | More flexible                  |

3️⃣ Simple Mental Model

Mock says:

“This must happen.”

Spy says:

“Let’s see what happened.”

4️⃣ Real-World Comparison

Imagine this service:

class PaymentProcessor
  def call(user)
    NotificationService.send_email(user)
  end
end
Using Mock
expect(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)

You’re declaring expectation upfront.

Using Spy
allow(NotificationService).to receive(:send_email)

PaymentProcessor.new.call(user)

expect(NotificationService).to have_received(:send_email)

You observe behavior after.

5️⃣ When to Use What?
🔹 Use Mock when:

Interaction is critical

You want strict behavior testing

In pure interaction-driven design

🔹 Use Spy when:

You want more natural test flow

Following Arrange → Act → Assert style

Cleaner readability

Many developers prefer spy style because it feels more structured:

Arrange
Act
Assert

🎯 Interview-Ready Answer

If interviewer asks:

“What is difference between mock and spy in RSpec?”

You say:

A mock sets an expectation before execution using expect(...).to receive, while a spy verifies interaction after execution using have_received. Both test method calls, but spies follow an Arrange-Act-Assert pattern and are generally more flexible.

That’s a strong answer.

